properties.name: Chinese New Year Festival 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing  Dr.Sun Yat-Sen Classical Chinese Garden, Sunday, Jan. 29,2006 from 10:00am to 4:30pm, by donation. Chinese New Year Festival Celebrate the Year of the Dog with sound, color, and joy. The Garden’s plum blossom trees will be in full bloom signifying the return of spring. Chinatown and the Garden will be decorated for the biggest festival in the Chinese calendar. Activities include fortune telling, martial arts, calligraphy writing, storytelling, lucky red packets, and a special exhibition of traditional New Year arts by the Chinese Canadian Artists Federation. Watch for the big parade that winds through the streets of Chinatown around noon!

properties.name: Chinese New Year Jan. 27-29, 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing  51 Prince\'s Bvd, toronto, Ontario"Festival\'s got it all to amaze and amuse," announces the Toronto Star headline. It further says, "The three days event boasts ancient art and modern fun." Yes, we are back to celebrate Lunar New Year. 2006 will be year 4704, according to our ancient calendar, and it will be the year of the Dog! Our original Chinese theme has expanded to include other Asian communities that celebrate the Lunar New Year, such as: Korea, Japan, Vietnam, Thailand, Burma, Laos and also Chinese-speaking communities from Philippines, Indonesia, India, Singapore, Malaysia and others. Let us celebrate together. Let Toronto celebrates Lunar New Year!

properties.name: Chinese New Year Parade 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing  san francisco, CaSaturday, February 11, 2006 5:30 pm. Named one of the top ten Parades in the world by IFEA, the Southwest Airlines Chinese New Year Parade in San Francisco is one of the few remaining night illuminated Parades in the country. Started in the 1860\'s by the Chinese in San Francisco as a means to educate the community about their culture, the Parade and Festival have grown to be the largest celebration of Asian culture outside of Asia. Since 1958, the parade has been under the direction of the Chinese Chamber of Commerce. The Parade goes up Market to Geary St, then goes right on powell for a block before taking another right on Post. It then turns right on Kearney St, where it goes on for a few blocks to its end point

properties.name: Chinese New Year, Jan. 28, 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing  200 S. 6th Avenue, Tucson, AZUsher in the Year of the Dog with the Tucson Chinese School at the annual Chinese New Year festival on Saturday, January 28, 2006 at the Tucson Children\'s Museum. Families will enjoy dance performances, singing, calligraphy demonstrations, and craft-making activities at the festival. This event is scheduled from 1:00 PM to 4:00 PM and is included in the price of admission. Families attending the festival will see a performance of the Lion Dance, listen to traditional songs sung in Chinese, enjoy a children\'s dance, receive a New Year\'s saying written in Chinese calligraphy, and more. Students from the Tucson Chinese School will perform the energetic and colorful Lion Dance at the festival. This traditional dance is believed to drive away evil spirits and bring in good luck especially in the New Year. Festival guests will be able to take home a New Year\'s saying written in Chinese calligraphy. Chinese calligraphy has evolved into a worldwide art form greatly admired for the discipline and artistry involved in creating the strokes. Kids will also be able to take home a paper-cutting souvenir and learn how to make items with paper folding, courtesy of the Tucson Chinese School. The Tucson Chinese School is once again partnering with the Tucson Children\'s Museum in bringing this festival to the community. The school provides Chinese cultural and language classes once a week to children and adults. The Tucson Children\'s Museum began its Festivals of Light series in 2001, working together with cultural groups throughout the community to share holiday traditions with one another. The Festivals include music, dance, songs, stories and folk art traditions that can be enjoyed by the entire family. Each festival includes hands-on activities for children.

properties.name: Golden Dragon Parade 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing  North Broadway, Los Angeles, CA2-5 PM. Many events from Jan 29-Feb 17. See the website calendar for more information. Over one hundred years ago, the Chinese community began to participate in the parades of the City of Los Angeles. In 1898, the Chinese lion and dragon procession were regarded as one of the most beautiful units in the City\'s Annual La Fiesta Parade. After the Vietnam War in 1975, Indo-Chinese refugees poured into the United States and soon became active in our community. Local family associations, Buddhist temples, and community-based organizations mushroomed and the parade became a focal point for community participation. Without a doubt, the Golden Dragon Parade is the highlight of the Chinese New Year in Southern California. Parade starts at main Street and New High Street, then turns left up W Cesar chavez Ave, turning right on N Broadway, where it hits it\'s longest stride. It turns left on Bernard St and wraps back around to end at Hill Street between Alpine and Ord.

properties.name: Lion Dance Feb 12 2006
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing    Portland, ORThroughout the fifteen-day span of the traditional Chinese New Year, the Portland Classical Chinese Garden is proud to host a number of activities, performances, exhibits and special events. Join the Garden from January 29th to February 12th, 2006 in celebrating Chinese heritage by participating in traditional Chinese crafts and viewing various Chinese performing arts. The Garden\'s highly anticipated annual plant sale commences on Friday, February 3rd. This is our largest plant sale of the year and features many traditional Chinese New Year selections: Orchids, flowering Meyer\'s Lemons, potted kumquats, fragrant Buddha\'s Hand, Flying Dragon citrus, and Chinese Crab Claw narcissus will be complemented by a host of other plants, common and rare, all native to China. Garden events begin with a spectacular Lion Dance on Sunday, January 29th and will conclude on Sunday, February 12th with a traditional lantern festival hallmarked by a free lantern making workshop and procession through the Garden. Local martial arts groups will demonstrate Tai Chi and Qigong. Other activities include Dragon Arts Puppetry, Chinese Knot Tying, Calligraphy and Storytelling. The Garden also invites visitors to meet author and illustrator Grace Lin. Ms. Lin will be at the Garden on February 4th & 5th to read excerpts from her new book, The Year of the Dog and sign books.
